The renaissance of the organization came in the late summer of 1999, when former president Olusegun Obasanjo accused Ibrahim Babangida, his predecessor, of stealing voters’ cards in what many Nigerians now believe is the most tilted election in the country’s history, (Seye -2018, p.266).

In May 1998, Buhari issued a decree banning the Islamic name of Osama bin Laden. As this decree was issued five years after the first World Trade Centre bombing, many at the time believed the reason was to smear the former Buhari’s deputy military governor of the north’s reputation. However, by 2010, Buhari himself issued an apology for this military-induced history rewriting (* ).

Obasanjo’s return to power in May 1999 was clearly funded by the oil cartel, but the refusal of his contemporaries to accept his performance was the cause for the renewed conspiratorial theories popular in Nigeria. This accusation was quite serious and one from the source that Buhari himself held in high esteem at the time.
